<tr>
<td width="168" valign="top">   Trade in Services
  </td><td width="156" valign="top">   Malawi
  </td><td width="192" valign="top">   Rwanda and Uganda
  </td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width="168" valign="top">   Trade Related Areas
  </td><td width="156" valign="top">   Sudan
  </td><td width="192" valign="top">   DR Congo and Burundi
  </td>
</tr>

</table>
<p> To prepare the negotiations, each country will establish a National Development and Trade Policy Forum (NDTPF), which will be multisectoral and involve both government and non-state actors. Each NDTPF will send three representatives to a Regional Negotiating Forum (RNF), which will prepare ESA positions prior to negotiations with the EU. The secretariats of the regional organisations will act as the secretariat for the RNF. Ambassadorial spokespersons will be supported by small negotiating teams drawn from the RNF and regional organisations. The lead spokespersons will negotiate from written briefs prepared by the RNF and approved by the committee of ESA ambassadors and the ESA council of ministers. This will include 'fall back’ positions.</p><p> On agriculture the ESA will seek to negotiate:</p>
<ul>

<li>improved special and differential treatment to ensure that there is the increased flexibility needed for implementation of an EPA; </li>

<li>the preservation of the benefits obtained under the EBA initiative to ESA LDCs; </li>

<li>the preservation and improvement of existing market access of ESA states while taking into account existing commodity arrangements, time-frames, tariff-reduction percentages and the need to limit the loss of ESA benefits resulting from the erosion of preferences; </li>

<li>specific agricultural safeguards, given the centrality of agriculture; </li>

<li>a programme to build capacity in the agriculture sector; </li>

<li>commodity agreements for the importation into the EU of part of the ESA production of commodities in order to ensure a fair remuneration to ESA producers and a mechanism to provide an insurance to absorb the volatility in prices of commodities; </li>

<li>terms and conditions for the implementation of Article 36.4 of the Cotonou Agreement at the all-ACP level within the existing structures upon completion of the negotiations under the Doha Development Agenda and the reform of the EU sugar regime. </li>

</ul>
<p> The ESA group also wants to see 'the impact of the reform process of the CAP.... taken into account with a view to putting in place instruments and mechanisms that will safeguard the derived benefits’.</p><p> Other areas of significance in the agricultural sector that the ESA group will try to negotiate on include:</p>
<ul>

<li>a human-resource and institutional capacity-building programme financed by the EU to ensure the development of adequate mechanisms for sanitary and phytosanitary (SPS) and food-safety standards compliance, that will result in the efficient provision of adequate nationwide and, where appropriate, regional coverage; </li>

<li>the financing of projects aimed at the eradication of pests and diseases of economic importance to ESA agriculture; </li>

<li>upgrading of ESA slaughterhouses to EU standards and norms; </li>

<li>assistance in developing regional programmes on animal-health surveillance and monitoring; </li>

<li>assistance to enable ESA states to participate actively in the setting of internationally agreed standards and norms; </li>

<li>no change in SPS and environmental regulations unless there is a proven scientifically valid reason to do so which is supported by a valid risk assessment, and which allows the ESA a reasonable period of time to adjust before any new regulations are enforced; </li>

<li>implementation of a programme to develop self-regulation in exporters; </li>

<li>harmonised testing and certification standards throughout the EU, full transparency in tests used and adequate notification of new testing regulations </li>

<li>the development of a joint mechanism for co-ordination, consultation and exchange of information as regards notification and application of proposed SPS measures, whenever these measures might affect the interests of ESA states; </li>

<li>the undertaking of a comprehensive inventory of all SPS measures currently in force in the EU and its member states, including those already notified to the WTO. </li>

</ul>
<p> On the development dimension the ESA group will amongst other things seek to negotiate an adjustment facility to support budgetary adjustments and additional resources to assist with economic adjustments. The ESA Group will also seek to negotiate concrete programmes of support for production, marketing, distribution and transportation activities (PMDT).</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			

<ul>

<li> 
<a href="http://www.epawatch.net/documents/doc159_2.doc" target="_self">Joint 'Road Map’ to the ESA negotiations </a> </li>

</ul>
		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> It should be noted that unlike the EU the ESA grouping has no easily recognisable internal structures; as a consequence many of the discussions that will need to take place will be between ESA governments. This will require an intensive process of negotiations and rapid preparations at national level if the agreed timetable for the conduct of negotiations is to be adhered to. The detailed objectives being established by the ESA group highlights the extent of the differences in approach from those of the Commission as exemplified in the statements by Commissioner’s Lamy and Nielsen at the seventh JPA meeting in Addis Ababa.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

